{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f2f51568-b794-4c7d-904f-6189fa4b95d6","content":"The `dump-collect` skill I have available is specifically for **collecting** crash dumps, not analyzing them. For **analyzing** an existing `.dmp` file, here are your best options:\n\n### `dotnet-dump analyze`\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze <path-to-file.dmp>\n```\nUseful commands inside the analyzer:\n- `clrstack` — managed call stack\n- `pe` — print last exception\n- `dumpheap -stat` — heap summary\n- `threads` — list all threads\n\n### Other Tools\n- **Visual Studio** — open the `.dmp` directly for rich debugging\n- **lldb** with SOS plugin (Linux/macOS)\n- **WinDbg** with SOS (Windows)\n\nWould you like help setting up any of these tools in your environment?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8279854b-53c3-4cc2-9327-1a575e07c043","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description explicitly says:\n\n- USE FOR: enabling automatic crash dumps, capturing dumps, setting up dump collection\n- DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\n\nSo the dump-collect skill is NOT appropriate here since the user wants to analyze an existing dump, not collect one.\n\nLet me provide guidance on analyzing crash dumps myself.","outputTokens":337},"id":"88900bd0-a775-44e6-a4f2-5dbaef467f45","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:06:57.765Z","parentId":"090612d7-3385-454d-8a9f-43ca94ffcef6"}
